F requency and freedom in its use are therefore characteristic of ordinary speech, and of comedy and satire, the literary departments most nearly . allied to ordinary speech. Vergil avoids harsh elision, but other- wise is noted for his freedom. With Ovid the use of elision diminished rapidly,and the process continued until in the late poets it practically reached the vanishing point. Tibullus was notably careful in this important matter ; but the observations of Hoerschelmann¹ show that there was considerable development between books 1 anda.
